[[Image:Forest at Leivonmäki NP.JPG|thumb|300px|right|Forest of ''Pinus sylvestris'' with an [[understory]] of ''[[Calluna vulgaris]]'' in [[Leivonmäki National Park]], [[Finland]].]] The '''Scandinavian taiga''' is an [[ecoregion]] within the [[Taiga|Taiga and Boreal forests]] [[Biome]] as defined by the [[World Wide Fund for Nature|WWF]] classification (ecoregion PA0608).<ref name='er608'>{{cite web|title=Scandinavian and Russian taiga |url=http://www.eoearth.org/view/article/184753/ |website=Encyclopedia of the Earth |accessdate=December 31, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304102811/http://www.eoearth.org/view/article/184753/ |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |df= }}</ref> It is situated in [[Northern Europe]] between [[tundra]] in the north and [[temperate mixed forests]] in the south and occupies about 2,156,900&nbsp;km² (832,800&nbsp;mi²) in [[Norway]], [[Sweden]], [[Finland]] and the northern part of European [[Russia]], being the largest ecoregion in Europe. In Sweden the taiga is primarily associated with the [[Norrland terrain]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Sporrong |first=Ulf |chapter=The Scandinavian landscape and its resources |editor-last=Helle |editor-first=Knut|date=2003 |title=The Cambridge History of Scandinavia |publisher=Cambridge University Press |issue=1 |pages=22 }}</ref>
==Description== The Scandinavian and Russian taiga consists of [[conifer]]ous [[forest]]s dominated by ''[[Pinus sylvestris]]'' (in drier locations), often with an understory of ''[[Juniperus communis]]'', ''[[Picea abies]]'' and ''[[Picea obovata]]'' and a significant admixture of ''[[Betula pubescens]]'' and ''[[Betula pendula]]''. ''[[Larix sibirica]]'' is characteristic of the eastern part of the ecoregion.
It is bordered by the ecoregions of [[Scandinavian coastal conifer forests]] (west), [[Scandinavian Montane Birch forest and grasslands]] (northwest and upwards in the highlands and mountains), [[Kola Peninsula tundra]] (North), [[Northwest Russian-Novaya Zemlya tundra]] (northeast), [[Urals montane tundra and taiga]] (east) and [[Sarmatic mixed forests]] (south), by the [[Baltic Sea]] and [[White Sea]]. Geobotanically, it belongs to the Northeastern European [[floristic province]] of the [[Circumboreal Region]] of the [[Holarctic Kingdom]]. [[Image:Archangelsk taiga.JPG|thumb|left|350px|Taiga forest near [[Archangelsk]]]] [[Image:RanelvaIllhoellia C.JPG|thumb|right|350px|There are many rivers and lakes in the Taiga. Norwegian closed-canopy boreal forest at the Arctic Circle in [[Rana, Norway|Rana]].]]
{{-}} {{Paleartic boreal forests/taiga}}
